    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Regarding the question you ask above, I've been thinking... If instead we make shift-enter and _all_ new cell creation commands (new above, new below, alt-enter) consistently put the new cell in edit mode, I think it will lead to a more consistent/fluid experience.\n\nI'm finding that in most cases, when I make a new cell I want to edit it.  It's kind of weird to get a new cell made and not be able to type immediately into it (I know there's the possibility I may want to change its type, but more often than not I just want to do something in the cell itself).\n\nAnd if we make also shift-enter put us in edit mode, the very frequent case of repeated shift-enter to go through a notebook one cell at a time isn't lost: since shift-enter works in edit mode as much as in command mode, nothing changes there.\n\nWhat do you think? It would simplify the logic since there wouldn't be corner cases (like the last cell being different), instead the logic would be: \n\n\"Execution with shift-enter and any new cell command gives you an editable cell immediately; you can run it with another shift-enter to keep moving down or directly type into it. Switch to cmd mode if you need to manipulate the cell before doing anything with its contents, like changing its type\".\n\nThoughts?\n"
  },
