    "body": "Regarding the question you ask above, I've been thinking... If instead we\nmake shift-enter and _all_ new cell creation commands (new above, new\nbelow, alt-enter) consistently put the new cell in edit mode, I think it\nwill lead to a more consistent/fluid experience.\n- That means even if you are in the middle of a notebook `shift+enter` will\n  edit the following cell. In the middle of a notebook that is almost never\n  what you want to do.\n- Right now (and probably for 2.0) new cells are always code cells. As long\n  as that is the case, always entering edit mode on cell creation is too\n  much. For example, to get a new Markdown cell in edit mode you would have\n  to: insert above, esc to enter command mode, m to get markdown cell, return\n  to get in edit mode. If we can better guess which type of cell (I am not\n  sure we can) a user wants, this situation would be helped.\n\n> I'm finding that in most cases, when I make a new cell I want to edit it.\n> It's kind of weird to get a new cell made and not be able to type\n> immediately into it (I know there's the possibility I may want to change\n> its type, but more often than not I just want to do something in the cell\n> itself).\n> \n> And if we make also shift-enter put us in edit mode, the very frequent\n> case of repeated shift-enter to go through a notebook one cell at a time\n> isn't lost: since shift-enter works in edit mode as much as in command\n> mode, nothing changes there.\n\nYes, that experience would be maintained.\n\n> What do you think? It would simplify the logic since there wouldn't be\n> corner cases (like the last cell being different), instead the logic would\n> be:\n> \n> \"Execution with shift-enter and any new cell command gives you an editable\n> cell immediately; you can run it with another shift-enter to keep moving\n> down or directly type into it. Switch to cmd mode if you need to manipulate\n> the cell before doing anything with its contents, like changing its type\".\n\nAfter working with the recently reversed swapped state for a few weeks\n_everyone_ was in complete agreement that we should swap back. I think the\nbest thing to do is to use it in the current state for a while longer and\nsee what everyone thinks. In this case, experiment is better than all my\nabove theories...\n"
  },
